path.
Continue renaming the Filer.
Include Dejavu font licence file when building the image.
Update README.

Filer improvements.

Render multiple columns of files side by side in Filer instead of falling
off the bottom of the window.
Colourise file names based on their type.
Load more source files.
Let NIC drivers complete init before setting up the network stack.

Panic when reading from the serial stream instead of calling ERROR.

ERROR would tend to generate endless nested errors, eventually overflowing
the stack and crashing the system anyway.
Move file-server IP and source paths out of ipl.lisp into a separate file.
Load the HTTP filesystem.
Change desktop picture.
Load swank.
Enable transparency by default.
Clean up ipl.lisp a little.
Be less verbose when saving the freelist.
Rename disk_header to disk-header.bin

Be less noisy when a window becomes responsive/unresponsive.

The system would chug a bit while the enormous message was printed
to the serial port.
Swank server.
Improve DESCRIBE for threads.
Improve REMOVE/DELETE(-IF(-NOT)).
Allow TCP streams to be closed multiple times.
Add force argument to CAL.

Rebind the active handler list properly when signalling a condition.

"Handlers are invoked in a dynamic environment equivalent to that of the
signaler, except that the set of active handlers is bound in such a way as to
include only those that were active at the time the handler being invoked was
established."
SIGNAL was incorrectly removing all active handlers when a handler
was being invoked.
Fix associativity of REDUCE when FROM-END is specified.
Fix slot-exists-p/-boundp/-makunbound on funcallable standard instances.
Add reader functions for debug info.
Store the namestring of the compile-file-pathname in the debug-info.
Avoid creating zero-dimensional arrays when NIL is passed to MAKE-FIFO.
Fix TCP servers.

Fix list & vector structs.

They had bitrotted and not been updated for the new struct-based slot
definitions.
Print the device id when performing the initial PCI scan.
Change the network light colour, it was nearly invisible before.
Send a RST if the remote does not hang up quickly in FIN-WAIT-2.
Make the IRC client slightly more user-friendly.
Copy the doc directory.
Bump the LLF version, been a while.
Update copyright year.
Stuff for loading the sources into the image.
Prompt for a server name when starting telnet.
Automatically configure ASDF and remove stale comment.
Rename FS-Viewer to Filer.
Remove the old editor in favour of MED.
Bloop
Silence normal pager/allocation messages.
Add a light for network activity.
Keep lights on for longer, makes them more noticeable.
Add memory-monitor to the initial load and desktop.

MAKE-FUNCTION-WITH-FIXUPS was allocating one too many words.

This was causing a simple-vector to be created after each new function.
Log when an unsupported PCI or Virtio device is detected.
Fix loading from non-FILE-STREAM streams.

Avoid creating bignums when marking pinned objects.

Backend creates functions with large lumps of GC metadata, causing the
function header to be larger than a fixnum.
Avoid creating bignums in MAKE-IDT-ENTRY.

Fix nested early panic.

*CURRENT-FRAMEBUFFER* may be unbound if SET-PANIC-LIGHT is called
very early.

Generate proper GC metadata when returning multiple values.

This was only a problem if a function was interrupted on the RET just
before returning multiple values and a GC cycle ran while the thread
was interrupted. Unlikely.

Fixups can only be used with 32-bit signed immediates.

Use assert to make this clear.
Fix typo in GC-INFO-FOR-FUNCTION-OFFSET.
Use CAS in ACQUIRE-MUTEX instead of the low-level struct-cas function.
Physical memory usage visualizer.

Remove %RESCHEDULE and %%SWITCH-TO-THREAD.

They're redundant with %RESCHEDULE-VIA-WIRED-STACK
Shuffle thread.lisp around a bit. Trying to untangle it
Simplify CREATE-SUPPORT-OBJECTS.
Encapsulate structure slot definitions in a struct, instead of using a list.

Reimplement spinlocks using the new CAS macro.

This makes them SMP-safe.

Implement generic CAS.

Works on structure slots and symbol-global-value.

When allocating new wired address space, immediately back that memory.

Leaving it to the page-fault handler will cause the system to panic,
as page-faults on wired memory are not permitted.
ZEROIZE-PHYSICAL-PAGE and MAKE-EPHEMERAL-THREAD.
Use FILL-WORDS/COPY-WORDs in ZEROIZE-PAGE and FAST-COPY-PAGE.
Basic ACPI support, enough to read the MADT table.
Update to KBoot-new.

Eliminate the per-instance funcallable-instance trampoline.

Funcallable instances now work similarly to closures, they have a single
global function that deals with invocation.
The difference them that the trampoline used for the standard function
calling convention, not the fref convention.
Required because the target function can change after the object is
created.
Update BUILD and README.
Adjustable compositor framerate.
Clean up the CPU code a little, in preperation for SMP.

Avoid double-unlocking threads in %%SWITCH-TO-THREAD-COMMON.

This only happens when returning to the same thread.

Move the RAISE-foo-ERROR functions into error.lisp.

They were overwritting the early error functions in the supervisor,
moving them later in the cold load make debugging very early errors
easier.

New bootloader version.

The %%BOOTLOADER-ENTRY-POINT hack has been removed and the bootloader
now passes the physical address of the ACPI RSDP in the boot info.
Defer the GC instead of disabling interrupts in CPUID.
Move low-level network init stuff into a seperate function.
Preempt threads.
Remove the old %BITBLT/%BITSET functions.
Clean up the arguments to FILL-/BLIT-WITH-CLIP.

Poll the serial port instead of using interrupts.

The old code was wildly incorrect and was reenabling interrupts while on
the wired stack.
Fix typo. TYPE-ERROR -> RAISE-TYPE-ERROR.
Set the run light as soon as video gets initialized.
Convert the GUI to premultiplied alpha.
Stream class wrapping disk access.
More debug logging in the physical allocator.
Remove incorrect IGNORE declaration in FLOAT.
Print AST-CALL nodes nicely and unparse suppliedp arguments properly.
Make data flow in the MAPCAR/MAPLIST compiler macros more obvious.
Implement LIST and AND types.
Compiler pass to simplify control flow.
Fix bug when merging TAGBODYs.
Avoid inserting extra statements into TAGBODYs when possible.
Merge nested TAGBODY AST nodes.
Use one form per go-tag in TAGBODY-AST.

Remove FLUSH-FORM.

It hasn't been used properly for a while, and the compiler doesn't
really make use of it.

Simplify AST nodes based on how many values they're expected to produce.

This converts (foo (values a)) into (foo a), turns BLOCK into TAGBODY
when the result isn't used, and similar transforms.
Add width/height arguments to basic-repl:spawn.
Fix PROGN body simplification.
Simplify all TAGBODY statements, and the BLOCK body.
Clean up SIMP-PROGN-BODY, make sure it calls simp-form on all forms.
Remove some side-effect free nodes in tagbody bodies.
Remove code after RETURN-FROM as well as GO in TAGBODYs.
Update HOIST-FORM-OUT-OF-IF.

Fix compiler bugs when flattening tagbodies.

Flattening nested tagbodies didn't work at all and sometimes GO tags
were being dropped when they shouldn't have been.
Printers for SPECIAL-VARIABLE, AST-FUNCTION and AST-QUOTE.
Add a function for generating compiler AST objects from lists.
Represent special variables in the compiler using a class.
Use generic functions instead of typecasing on ast nodes.
Descend into LET binding init-forms when removing temporaries.
AST node for TAGBODY forms.
AST node for GO forms.
AST node for RETURN-FROM forms.
AST node for BLOCK forms.
AST node for LET forms.
AST node for UNWIND-PROTECT forms.
AST node for jump table forms.
AST node for THE forms.
AST node for MULTIPLE-VALUE-CALL.
AST node for MULTIPLE-VALUE-PROG1.
AST node for MULTIPLE-VALUE-BIND.
Split CG-FUNCTION-FORM into smaller functions.
AST node for FUNCTION forms.
AST node for PROGN forms.
AST node for SETQ.
AST node for normal by-name calls.
AST node for IF forms.
AST node for QUOTE forms.

Replace compiler structs with classes.

They were originally structs because of issues with bootstrapping, but
these have been solved. Switching over to classes should make it easier
to develop the compiler.
Change LAMBDA-INFORMATION-BODY to be one form, not a list of forms.

Faster single dispatch.

Use a custom hash-table implementation for 1-effective dispatch functions.
This is much faster than the current CL:HASH-TABLE implementation.

Instructions required for a simple cached method call have gone from
4,800 instructions to just 800. There is a noticable speedup during
initialization.
Tool for generating Bochs-compatible map files.
WITH-PROFILER, to profile a form and save the results somewhere.
Fix typo in error when calling a GF with no matching primary methods.

Rewrite Virtio-Net RX handling. This should fix the missing RX buffer bug.

Packets are now allocated on demand during receive processing instead of
having a semi-preallocated list of buffers.
Constant propagate FUNCTION forms.

Fix MULTIPLE-VALUE-BIND when binding special variables.

M-V-B on special variables gets converted to M-V-B on lexical variables,
which are then used to let-bind the original special variables.
The use counts on these lexical variables were not being set correctly
and they were being incorrectly removed.
Signal an error when a variable in a let/let* binding is not a symbol.
Constant fold BINARY-=

Fold IF with a constant test in the simplify pass.

This is also done by the code generator, but doing it at a higher level
enables more optimizations.
Remove old symbol from the supervisor package.
Fix a few address sign-extension bugs.
Add START/END arguments to BSEARCH.

Report when ATAPI devices are detected.

This is to distinguish between an actual IDENTIFY failure and ATAPI
devices.
Implement negative addresses in (SETF PHYSICAL-PAGE-VIRTUAL-ADDRESS).
Track how many new objects the GC finds during a cycle.

Compute the approximate CPU speed in Hz.

This'll be used for converting cycle counts to nicer units, like seconds.
Don't print nonexistent PCI devices during the boot scan.

Track how much time was spent transporting objects in the GC.

Objects are divided up into power-of-two sized bins and times are tracked
sepeartely for each bin.
Small <=16-byte objects take most of the time to copy (probably conses),
followed by <=64-byte objects, then large megabyte+ objects.
Update build instructions. Network config and disk image/ram size.
Add a :WIRED argument to LOAD, to allow loading into the wired area.
GC before taking the last cold-init snapshot. Reduces disk requirements.

Improve PCI device support.

PCI config space can safely be accessed from normal threads now, but
PCI IO regions are still unsafe to access.

Seperate virtio-net TX & RX code.

I'll fix the RX buffer bug eventually, but this seems to make it go away.
Don't allocate during THROW.

Implement a fast path for page faults on fresh zero pages.

After the system boots and the first GC of that boot, almost all further
page faults are on zero pages.
Allow mutexes to be trylocked when interrupts are disabled.

Don't stop the world with *VM-LOCK* held.

This can deadlock with the pager if there are PA threads waiting for pages.
Track time spent in the GC.

Write the deferred freelist to disk, and handle multi-block freelists.

The system appears to be usable again, but it leaks blocks.

Use a dedicated normal thread to run post-boot actions.

This thread can be reused every boot, meaning that BOOTLOADER-ENTRY-POINT
only needs to allocate the stack on the first boot. Subsequent boots
may not have enough disk space available without running a GC, which can't
be done from the initial thread.

Update the snapshotter for the new swappy world.

It's mostly functional now, but there are bugs.
It leaks disk blocks, and sometimes the freelist becomes too complicated
to fit in a single block.

Be pseudo-atomic when expanding areas.

Areas are expanded in two operations. One to expand newspace, and one to
expand oldspace. These must be done while pseudo-atomic or another thread
can trigger a GC between the two expansions.
Use a function to check page-alignedness instead of open coding it.
The 64-bit buddy allocator covers 39 address bits, not 36.
Give up when a stack can't be allocated.
Implement DESCRIBE on ratios and complex numbers.
Move PPRINT-INDENT to its proper home.

Do not handle page faults until the paging disk has been found.

If a snapshot is taken when threads in the wait-for-page state, then this
will persist into the next boot. The pager will immediately try to resolve
these page faults during boot, and fail because the block map will not
have been initialised.
Delaying the pager until the paging disk has been found and read fixes
this.

Always (re)initialize thread frame pointers.

This isn't strictly needed for regular threads, but without it ephemeral
threads can end up with loops in their stack frames.

Make sure that zero pages get swapped out properly.

This isn't quite as efficient as it could be, but ideally nothing should
ever swap.

Fix recursive freelist metadata allocation.

PAGER-ALLOCATE-PAGE may call back into the store functions, requiring
more metadata to be allocated. Maintain a minimum number of free
metadata objects during use, and only dip into them during a recursive
call.
Implement cross SAVE-ONE-OBJECT for ratios.
Replace WAIT-FOR-HEARTBEAT calls with SLEEP.

Rework locking in store.lisp.

Store functions are now protected by *VM-LOCK*, not by interrupts &
spinlocks. ALLOC & FREE require *VM-LOCK* to be held before calling.

The recent swap changes have made the pager & snapshot threads the only
threads to call the store functions, so complex page-fault-safe locking
is no longer required.

Fix a some misuses of %CLI and %RESCHEDULE.

These were disabling interrupts while running on a normal pagable thread
stack.

Incomplete swap support.

The system was able to do a complete cold load with 32MB, but there's at
least one memory corruption bug involving zero pages that I can't
reproduce.
Snapshotting is currently broken.

Replace *MEMORY-EXPANSION-REMAINING* with feedback from the VM system.

Instead of guessing how much memory is available, the system now knows
when it has run out of memory and will run the GC based on this.
Fix off-by-one error when writing to the last block on a disk.

Disable the page fault handlers IST when panicing.

Page faults when printing the panic backtrace during a fatal page fault
would occasionally cause circular stack frames to be created, leading to
infinite and mostly useless backtraces.

Run allocate/release/protect-memory-range in the pager thread.

Previously these were run in the context of the calling thread. Normal
threads have pageable stacks, which require the pager to page them in.
If a thread took a stack page fault while in a foo-memory-range function
with the *VM-LOCK* held, the system could deadlock. By running them in
the pager thread, this problem is avoided because the pager is wired.
Fix typo in code that scans thread MV areas.

New physical memory information array layout.

Having a single type field instead of multiple status bits should make
the various possible page modes clearer, in preperation for swapping.
Snapshotter has not been updated and is broken.
Implement LOAD-TIME-VALUE.
Update kboot.

Move BSEARCH into a file that is actually used.

The local filesystem uses it.

Fix a bug that caused multiple values to appear where they shouldn't.

(LET ((X (VALUES 1 2))) X) and similar forms were being optimized to
(VALUES 1 2). They're now correctly converted to (VALUES (VALUES 1 2)),
limiting to a single value.
Implement RASSOC(-IF(-NOT)).
Partially implement ENOUGH-NAMESTRING and the $ FORMAT control.

Avoid mangling literals in the compiler.

The lower-special-bindings pass was inserting literal data into the AST,
which a subsequent simplify pass was mangling.

Bind *ALLOW-DX-ENVIRONMENT* in LOWER-ENVIRONMENT.

Sometimes the value would leak out to the global environment and it
would get set to NIL. Not a problem, just not clean.
Add restarts to EXPORT and INTERN.

Fix COERCE-VECTOR-ELEMENT-TYPE for unspecialized vector types.

It was returning * when it should have returned T.
This fixes (make-sequence 'vector ...).
Implement NSUBSTITUTE(-IF) and MAP-INTO.
Implement SLOT-UNBOUND.
Implement PROBE-FILE & TRUENAME properly.
Fix EQL's GC metadata.
Expunge the old CSP/CFP aliases for RSP/RBP.
Add missing lock prefix to atomic add function.
Fix typo in MAKE-ARRAY.

Write the entire *foo-AREA-DATA* vector when generating the cold image.

These vectors and the area sizes are both 2MB aligned. Writing the
entire vector out prevents uninitialized data from being left between
the bump pointer and the end of the area, which would then be returned
by the low level allocation functions.
Implement :IF-EXISTS :SUPERSEDE on the local filesystem.

Make the fundamental allocation functions more robust.

Pinned/wired allocation will call the GC instead of panicing if there
is not enough space.
Allocators wont get stuck in a GC loop if the allocation fails (requires
a GC) *MAXIMUM-ALLOCATION-ATTEMPTS* times, instead they'll signal a
STORAGE-CONDITION using ERROR.

Cold generator improvements.

A file-stream can be passed as the image name, and MAKE-IMAGE will
write to that instead of creating a new output file.
The path to the map file can be specified, instead of being derived from
the image name.
An image generated without a header-path or image-size will be as small
as possible. It's assumed that it'll be dd'd onto a real partition.
Add a compositor shortcut to recompose the whole screen (M-F1).
Implement support for using UB8 vectors when accessing the disk.
Calculate the image size from the disk size, don't keep it in the header.
Make the TCP stack slightly more conforming.
Add a REBOOT function.

Remove the repl from INITIALIZE-LISP.

It was causing problems with the debug video console.
RTL8168 driver.
Increase the granularity of GET-INTERNAL-REAL/RUN-TIME slightly
Deal with non-page-aligned PCI MMIO regions properly.
Add padding to the video console. It was wrapping and causing panics.

Correctly detect PCI bridges in multifunction devices.

The high bit of the header type field indicates a mulitfunction device,
it's not part of the actual header type.
Don't wait quite as long when probing for disks.
Implement SLEEP.
Add LBA48 support to the ATA driver.
Allow multiple IRQ handlers to share an IRQ.

Remove WITH-FONT and CLOSE-FONT.

WITH-FONT can be replaced with OPEN-FONT, and CLOSE-FONT calls can be
removed entirely.
Bump LLF version. Full rebuild required after all these changes.
Fix RESTART-CASE's restart ordering.
WITH-PACKAGE-ITERATOR's access type and package values were swapped.
Deal with partially initialized threads properly in the GC.
Implement FORMATTER.

Convert RATIOs and COMPLEX numbers to non-struct objects.

This makes them use the proper type tags, fixing EQL.
Check the type of the struct in struct accessors.
Fix C&P bug in LATCH-TRIGGER.
APROPOS and APROPOS-LIST both take string designators.
APROPOS returns no values.
Implement READ-FROM-STRING's second return value.
Implement WITH-INPUT-FROM-STRING's index argument.

Realign the stack before calling RAISE-TYPE-ERROR in %APPLY.

%APPLY pushes values one by one, if a type error occurs after processing
an odd number of arguments, then RAISE-TYPE-ERROR would have been called
with a misaligned stack.
WARN can only warn about WARNINGs, not arbitrary conditions.
ASSOC should ignore NIL entries in the alist.

Only inhibit footholds in the inner allocation loop.

This might give M-Esc a chance at interrupting a thread stuck in a GC
loop.
Obey *READ-SUPPRESS* in the #A reader.
LOGAND/IOR/XOR only operate on integers, not numbers.
PUSHNEW should evaluate to the new value of the place.
BY, ABOVE and DOWNTO are valid ways to start a loop FOR clause.

Associate a thread with each window and add a command to interrupt a window.

Use M-Esc to attempt to break into the debugger. This doesn't always work
as ESTABLISH-THREAD-FOOTHOLD doesn't support interrupting a thread in an
arbitrary state.

Implement BASE-CHAR and EXTENDED-CHAR using DEFTYPE.

They're simple, no need to special-case them.
Signal more precise/standards-compliant errors, instead of simple-error.

Fix off-by-one error in the symbol binding code.

Symbol TLS slot ids are regular slot indexes, indexing into the thread
code. +TLS-BASE-OFFSET+ was causing symbol accessors to access from the
very start of the thread object, not from the address of the first slot.

This caused TLS accesses to the very first bound symbol, which was
*ACTIVE-CATCH-HANDLERS*, to overwrite the last multiple-values slot.
This slot was always initialized to 0, not to the tls unbound value,
causing the chain of catch tags/handlers to have an invalid terminator.

MAKE-THREAD worked around this bug when setting initial bindings.
Fix the small (un)signed-byte specialized arrays.

Inhibit some forms of inlining when building Chipz.

Recent compiler changes seem to have made it more enthusiastic about
inlining local functions. Chipz's decompressor uses lots of mutually-
recursive local functions, which causes the compiler to run out of memory.
Fix constant propagation bugs in the compiler.
Be more aggressive when flattening implicit progns.
DOLIST must evaluate the result form with the iteration variable bound.
Fix SIMP-TAGBODY when the tagbody contains exactly one go-tag and no statements

Fix go-tagless tagbody elimination.

The resulting form was not evaluating to NIL.
Fix return value of MULTIPLE-VALUE-SETQ.

Fix MULTIPLE-VALUE-BIND binding special variables.

SIMP-IMPLICIT-PROGN returns nothing and modifies the progn body in-place.
Stuff building a new form needs to use the old form...
Fix COPY-FORM. It was mishandling &OPTIONAL/&KEY parameters.
Fix inlining of special &rest variables.
Make FDEFINITION work on all special operators.
Return the right value when setting character arrays.
Rename the STRUCTURE-CLASS function to avoid conflicting with CL.
A matching (E)TYPECASE clause should evaluate to NIL if the body is empty.
Signal the correct error type in ECASE.
%INVALID-ARGUMENT-ERROR was renamed to RAISE-INVALID-ARGUMENT-ERROR.
Fix SETF. Was expanding to LET instead of LET*.
Implement (SETF APPLY).
DEFMACRO should return the macro name.
Implement COPY-SYMBOL.

Make SETQ propagation slightly less broken.

Only slightly.

Implement EQL correctly.

EQL was not implemented correctly for non-immediate numbers, an
out-of-line version has been added and the compiler has be modified
to lower EQL with EQ-comparable constants to EQ.
Check array rank against array-rank-limit in MAKE-ARRAY.
Implement bit array functions.

Keep font files in memory.

Taking a snapshot of the font file when the a typeface was opened solves
a bunch of issues. If the original file goes away (delete, or remote fs
disconnected, etc), then the font will keep working.

Use weak-pointers in the font manager instead of ref-counting.

This simplifies programming slightly, open fonts no longer need to be
closed when they're no longer used.
Fix finalizer bug.

Move room into its own file.

It's gotten too complicated to stay in gc.lisp now.

Fully implement LAST.

This is just the implementation from the HyperSpec. Not sure why I didn't
use it initially.

Delay opening COMPILE-FILE's output file.

This reduces the chance that the remote fs will leave zero-size LLF
files lying around if the system crashes or is not cleanly shut down
when COMPILE-FILE is running.
Print the number of instances of each struct/class in (ROOM T).

Faster copy file.

Use FILE-LENGTH to get an approximate size, then only write what
READ-SEQUENCE reads.
The cold generator was not putting uninterned symbols in the wired area.
Make invalid pagefault handling slightly more flexible.
Fix 64-bit DMA in the ATA driver.
Store the hash-table's hash function instead of calculating it each time.

Implement weak mappings and finalizers.

This is the "Second try" implementation described in "Weak References:
Data Types and Implementation".
Weak pointers.

Initialize the dependents slot of class T.

This class is created by hand and I forgot to update it.
Don't steal focus when starting the desktop.
Attempt to obey *MEMORY-EXPANSION-REMAINING* when allocating stacks.

Low priority threads.

Low priority threads will only run when there are no normal priority
threads ready to run. The new GUI will use them for background processing
threads.
Fix function redefintion in ENSURE-GENERIC-FUNCTION.

Basic completion support in the REPL.

Press Tab to cycle through completions.

Remove %SVREF, replace it with %OBJECT-REF-T.

The environment lowering pass runs after the inlining passes, which
prevents %SVREF from being inlined.

Use %OBJECT-TAG and %OBJECT-HEADER-DATA in SCAN-OBJECT-1.

Safer than poking around directly in the object header.
Unify GC metadata decoding.
Implement DEBUG-SERIAL-FORCE-OUTPUT and use it in PANIC to avoid losing messages.
Use a constant, not a magic number.
Slightly speed up character read-sequence on file-server streams.
Print more output when ROOM is called in verbose mode.
Hoist hard-coded paths in the cold-generator out into variables.
Print the current package name in the debugger prompt.
Bump the LLF version number. CLOS internals have changed incompatibly.
Deal with subclasses and generic functions when reinitializing classes.
Make SLOT-foo functions update obsolete instances.
Make FAST-SLOT-READ/-WRITE update obsolete instances.
Implement cold-clear-input.

Incomplete class redefinition support.

Slot reader/writer methods currently fail to update instances.
Generic function EMF tables are not invalidated yet.
Subclasses are not refinalized.
Plus many probable bugs.

Store slot storage layout vectors in each (funcallable-)std-instance.

Preparing for class redefinition. Every instance needs to have a way
of tracking if is obsolete. When a class is redefined, a new layout vector
will be created and every old instance of that class will have a stale
layout cell. The storage layout vector was chosen because
UPDATE-INSTANCE-FOR-REDEFINED-CLASS only needs to know names & values of
the old slots, not the slot-defintion object.

No memory overhead for std-instances, this replaces the padding word.
Funcallable-std-instances have increased in size by two words.
Print conses in DEBUG-WRITE.
Allow instances of the various CLOS standard classes to be created safely.
Fix remote filesystem's newline translation.

Generic function improvements.

Generic functions have been stored in functions cells for a while now, so
FIND-GENERIC-FUNCTION can be eliminated.
DEFMETHOD can now implicitly define generic functions. A warning is
generated when this happens.

HTTP/file-system bridge.

Automatically installs itself as the "HTTP" host, so normal URLs will
work with anything that accepts a pathname.
Doesn't support caching, compression, HTTPS, encoding detection, etc.
Encode characters correctly when writing them to a TCP or REMOTE stream.
CLEAR-INPUT after entering the debugger.

Implement OPEN-STREAM-P, INPUT-STREAM-P and OUTPUT-STREAM-P.

Trying to follow Allegro's docs:
http://franz.com/support/documentation/6.0/doc/gray-streams.htm
Print function-references better.
Save hash-tables.
WITH-ACCESSORS.
Implement string comparison functions and CHAR/=.
Unify the ATA read & write paths slightly.
Fix off-by-one error in the ATA DMA code.
Trying to track down virtio-net receive bug.
Discard IPv4 packets that aren't address to a local interface.
Ignore errors when processing clients in the file-server.

Start the ethernet worker thread late.

Receiving packets before the rest of the stack is loaded will cause
errors in the worker thread.
Convert source/dest IP addesses to address objects when passing to the receive functions.
Give names to the TCP header fields.

Networking improvements.

Loopback support, both as an interface and in the Ethernet layer (send-to-
self).
IPv4 stack now responds to ping.
IPv4 routes have been simplified further, with the interface combined into
the gateway field.
IPV4-ROUTE now returns the interface and IP address of the next hop
instead of being tied to Ethernet.
Cleaned up IP header creation/inspection.
IP headers are validated better.
LOG-AND-IGNORE-ERRORS. IGNORE-ERRORS with logging.
Print a backtrace if a boot-hook fails.
Lock hash tables during access.

Set the PIT tick rate to 100Hz.

The default tick rate is 18Hz, this does not make for a very responsive
GUI. 100Hz is more than enough to make the GUI feel smooth.
Wrap IP routes in a class.
Wrap IPv4 addresses in structures.
Split net/ethernet.lisp into multiple files & packages.
Remove debugging messages.

Possibly fix the long-standing hash table bug.

I'm still not sure what the problem was, but I think that a garbage
collection was occuring (due to networking or similar, not the hash-table
code) after (SETF GETHASH) had computed the hash, and before
FIND-HASH-TABLE-SLOT ran. This would trigger a rehash, then
FIND-HASH-TABLE-SLOT would search the table with the *stale* hash, leading
to trouble.
Fix bug in the escaping dx bug fix.

Use SB-BSD-SOCKETS instead of IOLIB in the file-server.

IOLIB seems to have some problems with recent versions of SBCL. Anything
more recent thatn 1.2.7.
Remove old file.
Things either got much faster or I am bad at benchmarking.

Bump the LLF version.

Changes to the builtins are drastic enough that it's worthwhile rebuilding.
Distribute the contents of misc.lisp to more appropriate places.
Move support functions out of entry.lisp into a dedicated file.

Rename array-like to object.

The array-like name existed because there used to be tags dedicated to
symbols, structures, etc. These were all gradually converted to use a
representation similar to arrays, hence "array-like". Aside from conses,
there aren't any heap-allocated objects with special representations, so
the old name doesn't mean much now.

Fix a possible bug involving DX allocations and NLX.

(lambda ()
  (block nil
    (multiple-value-prog1 (foo)
      (bar (lambda () (return))))))

This code would establish a non-local exit, then create a dynamic-extent
object to hold the values from (FOO). If the lambda was then called
and the block returned from, then M-V-P1's cleanup code wouldn't be run
and the dynamic-extent root that was created would remain live after
the stack pointer was restored by the NLX.
The compiler now tracks when dynamic-extent roots are created and inserts
code to clear them as part of the NLX. The GC assists by ignoring any
DX roots that point below the stack pointer.

interrupts disabled, so the header word cannot be written safely.

Don't write to the disk freelist log in STORE-FREE.

The store freelist log (the on-disk representation) gets fully rebuilt
when a snapshot is taken.
Updating it causes blocks to be added to the block cache, which is
currently never trimmed. Unused cached blocks would build up and slow
down any accesses to the block cache.

the allocators & GC.

NOTE: All .LLF files must be rebuilt!
This completely solves the ever-expanding-stack problem that
MULTIPLE-VALUE-PROG1 had, makes the GC immune to stray stale DX values
and obsoletes the stack mark bit, which has been removed now.

DX values are now allocated using two different methods, depending on
whether their size is know at compile time or not.
If the size is known, then they will be allocated directly in the
function's stack frame as scannable/live values.
Otherwise, they are allocated on the stack, and a value to the object
tagged with +TAG-DX-ROOT-OBJECT+ will be stored in the stack frame. Only
objects can be allocated this way, not conses. Allocating an arbitrary
number of conses requires them to be wrapped in a simple-vector, possible
because conses are normally represented without any header.

The GC will ignore any values that point to the stack area unless they
have the +TAG-DX-ROOT-OBJECT+ tag. Such values are only permitted to
exist in a function's stack-frame. In other words, they are internal to
the GC and should not be treated as real Lisp values. A real Lisp value
must be tagged with +TAG-OBJECT+ instead. They should remain live for as
long as the dynamic-extent allocation.

Arbitrary-size allocations are not currently exposed by the compiler and
are only used internally for &REST lists and M-V-PROG1's value save area.

Pager cleanups

supervisor/pager: Extract a function for clearing a page to zeros.

  * Yet another oft-repeated code fragment.

supervisor/pager: Refactor page-table walk in GET-PTE-FOR-ADDRESS.

  * A lot of repeated code here, ripe for refactoring.  Extract
the core operation to a new function, DESCEND-PAGE-TABLE,
simplifying the overall control logic along the way.

supervisor/pager: Extract address-bit extractor functions.

  * There were quite a few repeated literal BYTE forms in here,
pretty much all without explanation.  Move them into functions, so
that it's more obvious both that they're all correct and what they
all are for.

supervisor/pager: Introduce trival wrappers for page-table entry hacking.

  * Rather than simply hacking up words in memory, hack up page
table entries, making it more obvious what's going on.

supervisor/pager: Extract new predicate, PAGE-PRESENT-P.

  * Following the theme of "tell me what you're doing, not how
you're doing it", extract a new predicate for the repeated test to
see if a given entry in a page table/directory/whatever is marked
as being "present".

supervisor/pager: Extract new function, FLUSH-TLB.

  * Rather than comment on what an opaque manipulation of some
system register does, extract the function so that we have a name
for the operation.  Then explain WHY the manipulation is correct,
rather than relying on a reader's intimate knowledge of x86oid
paged memory management.

Change function calling convention.

Every function now has an entry point, which is stored in the word
following the header. Functions must be invoked via this entry point now,
instead of jumping directly to the address.
SETF symbols have been removed in favour of a new object kind, treated
as an indirection for functions. Symbols no longer point to functions,
instead pointing to this new function reference object and setf functions
are also looked up via this object. Setf function names are currently
mapped to function references by symbol plists, but this may change in
the future.
Closures now cache their associated function's entry point and jump
directly there.

The Exorcism of the Second Stack: Part I

Completely eliminate the data stack from the compiler & stack-group code.
Removing the data stack & switching to a single stack with GC info model
will simplify the system and pave the way for improved code generation.
Interrupts & exceptions don't need to worry about preserving below the
stack pointer now, so interrupt stack groups can be eliminated.

APPLY & VALUES-LIST are now both implemented as assembly support functions.
Control stack sizes have been doubled to make up for the extra load, and to
take the space of the removed data stacks.
Backtracing must now examine return addresses and recover function objects
from them, instead of reading it from a magic stack slot.
The GC is broken, but will be fixed in part II or III!
Some assembly functions have been updated, some have not.

in the first place.

Environment analysis pass & lambda-list simplification.

This pushes environment analysis out of the codegen into a seperate pass,
greatly reducing variable-related complexity in the codegen.
Additionally, optional variables have been simplified so their init-forms
can only be constants and special variables in lambda lists are now bound
in the body of the function via let, again reducing complexity in the
codegen. Special lambda-list variables are now handled properly.

This opens the door to more complicated environment analysis. The new pass
combines environment vectors together when possible, usually reducing the
maximum depth.

Fix a bug in CG-UNWIND-PROTECT.

(let ((foo (unwind-protect (bar) ...))) ...)
The tag for bar would be generated correctly, but loaded into R8 and
killed too soon. UNBIND-TO smashes R8 when not generating multiple values,
because tag had been killed before unbind-to, smash-r8 would happily
clear r8 without saving, leading to a missing tag bug.

Deal with the bignum sign changing better in +/-.
The overflow flag is set when the sign changes, and the new sign can be
recovered from the carry flag. If the sign doesn't change then the carry
flag doesn't reflect the new state of the sign bit, so the last fragment
must be sign-extended.
